Structure of ant assemblages on street trees in urban Busan, Korea

Sang‐Hyun Park
Correspondence: Sang‐Hyun Park, Department of Biomedical Sciences, Kosin University, Dongsam‐dong, Yeongdo‐gu, Busan, 49104, South Korea. E‐mail:
Tae‐Young Moon
First published: 20 January 2020
https://doi.org/10.1111/1748-5967.12415
Sections
PDF
Tools
Share

Abstract

Street trees planted in urban areas are one of the smallest urban green habitats; however, their role as a valuable refuge for local biota is poorly understood. The aim of this study was to investigate urban street trees as habitat for ants. We found ants on 195 (92%) of 211 street trees studied. Seventeen ant species were collected from five tree species. The two most common ant species were Tetramorium tsushimae (on 112 trees) and Lasius japonicus (on 93 trees). The number of ant species found per tree ranged from 0 to 5, with a mean of 1.55 ± 0.92. The species composition differed significantly among tree species. Nine ant species (Camponotus vitiosus, Lasius alienus, L. japonicus, Nylanderia flavipes, Crematogaster matsumurai, Crematogaster vagula, Monomorium intrudens, T. tsushimae, and Brachyponera chinensis) nested on the trees, mostly in the root zone. Nests were found on 150 trees but were relatively rare on trees with diameter at breast height of less than 40 cm.

Introduction

Urban areas have been expanding (Botkin & Beveridge 1997; Lumsden & Bennett 2005; Ozanne et al. 2000), which has reduced the amount of vegetation. Remaining vegetation has been fragmented into patches of various sizes and shapes, leaving trees as relatively isolated individuals in the urban matrix (Dickman 1987; Rickman & Connor 2003). Associated with this fragmentation and loss of native vegetation are reductions in the complexity of microclimates and arthropod species richness, as well as a loss of native species and their replacement by exotics (Gibb & Hochuli 2002; McKinney 2006).

Vegetated areas within urban landscapes are increasingly seen as valuable refuges for local biota (Snep et al. 2006; Von Haaren & Reich 2006). Numerous studies have been conducted on arthropod communities in urban forest fragments (Nuckols & Connor 1995; Rickman & Connor 2003; Snep et al. 2006; Yui et al. 2001), residential gardens (Majer & Brown 1986), and clumps of trees in urban parks (McFrederick & LeBuhn 2006; Yamaguchi 2004). It is recognized that planting trees may be the only option to conserve local biota in urban areas, but very few studies have examined arthropod communities on isolated trees planted in urban areas (Bhullar & Majer 2000; Fischer & Lindenmayer 2002; Semlitsch & Bodie 1998).

Ants are found in almost all urban habitats (Klotz et al. 1995; Kondoh & Kitazawa 1984; Na & Lee 2001) and they can exert strong ecological (Folgarait 1998; Sanford et al. 2008) and economical effects (Klotz et al. 2008). In natural habitats, ant species can be predators, prey, detritivores, seed granivores, and herbivores (Alonso 2000; Folgarait 1998). In places where ants are rare, carrion and feces may decompose more slowly and are, therefore, more likely to accumulate than in places where ants are common (Frankie & Ehler 1978). Ants have been successfully used as indicators of ecosystem health under different agricultural practices and of the environmental changes that such practices inadvertently bring (Andersen et al. 2002; Lobry de Bruyn 1999; Peck et al. 1998). Ants can also provide an indication of the richness and types of ecological interactions to which humans in urban areas are exposed. It is important, therefore, to develop our understanding of ants living in urban areas. The aim of this study was to investigate whether street trees act as urban habitats for ants in cities. We sought to understand how the size and species of host trees influence the species richness and composition of ant assemblages. In addition, we evaluated the coexistence of particular sets of ant species on a single tree.

Materials and methods

The study site was Busan Metropolitan City (35°06′N, 129°06′E), Korea (Fig. 1). The city is located in a warm temperate region with an average annual rainfall of approximately 1519 mm (Korea Meteorological Administration, http://web.kma.go.kr). Seasonality is observed in both temperature and precipitation but winter is not severe, with only light snow and frost. Rainfall is concentrated in the summer (June–September), but there are no extremely dry months in the year.

We investigated 211 trees of more than 10 cm in diameter at breast height (DBH) for ant species composition and ant nests. Trees less than 10 cm DBH were not investigated as these would be not suitable for ant nesting (Klimes et al. 2015). Five tree species were investigated: Prunus × yedoensis (113), Machilus thunbergii (38), Ginkgo biloba (34), Liriodendron tulipifera (15), and Platanus orientalis (11) (Table 1).

Foraging ants were collected from the ground and tree trunks up to 200 cm above the ground, without using bait. No truly nocturnal species occur at the study site, therefore, sampling was conducted during the day, and was assumed to encompass all ant species and their activities. The investigations were carried out between July and October 2015. In all cases, the entrances of nests made in tree trunks and on the ground were visually confirmed.

To compare the species composition among trees, we constructed a similarity matrix using the Bray–Curtis similarity index (Kruskal & Wish 1978) using frequency data for each species. We then used group averaging cluster analysis to display different species assemblages. Significantly different clusters were identified using the similarity profile analysis (SIMPROF) in Primer 6 (Clarke et al. 2008). Additionally, we used Fisher's exact test (McDonald 2009) to test for associations between ant species. Scientific names of ants, and identification and arrangement of ant species, followed the guidelines of the Japanese Ant Database Group (2003).

Results

Ant richness, abundance, and species composition

Overall, we identified 17 ant species belonging to 13 genera in three subfamilies. We sampled ants from 195 (92%) of the 211 street trees: 15 species from P. × yedoensis, 11 from M. thunbergii, 4 from G. biloba, 2 from L. tulipifera, and 5 from P. orientalis (Table 2).

The number of ant species found per tree ranged from 0 to 5, with a mean of 1.55 ± 0.92. The average species richness of each tree species ranged from 0.53 ± 0.64 for L. tulipifera to 1.97 ± 0.97 for M. thunbergii. At least one ant species was observed on most trees: P. orientalis (100%), G. biloba (97.1%), P. × yedoensis (95.6%), and M. thunbergii (94.7%). In contrast, ants were found on fewer than half of L. tulipifera trees.

The most common ant species was Tetramorium tsushimae, which was found on 57.4% (112) of the 195 trees with ants, followed by Lasius japonicus (47.7%) (Fig. 2). Tetramorium tsushimae was found on all five tree species (Table 2). Tetramorium tsushimae was also most frequently found foraging on the ground (Table 2). On all 112 trees where this species was found, other ant species were found foraging on or near the same tree (Fig. 3). Lasius japonicus was the most frequently observed co‐forager (n = 33), with a statistically significant positive association between the two species (Fisher's exact test Χ2 = 20.68, Ptwo‐sided < 0.001). Other species frequently observed foraging with T. tsushimae were Camponotus vitiosus (n = 15) and Crematogaster matsumurai (n = 14). These co‐occurrences did not differ from random association (for C. vitiosus, Fisher's exact test Χ2 = 0.32, Ptwo‐sided = 0.697).

The cluster analysis separated ant assemblages into two groups: P. × yedoensis, M. thunbergii, and G. biloba, and L. tulipifera and P. orientalis (Fig. 4). The SIMPROF test showed that the ant species composition differed significantly among the tree species (P < 0.05).

Nests

Nine ant species—C. vitiosus, Lasius alienus, L. japonicus, Nylanderia flavipes, Cr. matsumurai, Crematogaster vagula, Monomorium intrudens, T. tsushimae, and Brachyponera chinensis—nested in the street trees. Most nests were found in the root zones. A total of 150 nests were found in the 211 trees surveyed (Table 2). In most cases, we observed only one nest per tree, however, several P. × yedoensis and M. thunbergii trees were inhabited by two ant colonies each. The combinations of ant species on these trees were T. tsushimae and L. japonicus, T. tsushimae and N. flavipes, T. tsushimae and Cr. matsumurai, T. tsushimae and Cr. vagula, L. japonicus and Cr. matsumurai, L. japonicus and Cr. vagula, L. japonicus and M. intrudens, and L. japonicus and B. chinensis. Each ant species pair appeared on a single tree. The nests of T. tsushimae were found in 69 (32.7%) of the trees (Table 2). The proportion of trees inhabited by ants ranged from 40.0% to 76.3% among the five tree species. Nests were relatively rare in trees with a DBH of less than 40 cm (Table 3).

Discussion

In the present study, 17 ant species belonging to 13 genera were observed on urban street trees in Busan. Harada (2011) and Iwata et al. (2005) reported 15 species from trees at Joyama Park and 18 species from trees at Nanatsujima Park, Kagoshima City, Japan, where climate conditions are similar to those of our study site. The mean number of ant species per tree was also not distinctly different between these studies (Joyama Park, 1.83 with a range from 0 to 6; Nanatsujima Park, 2.07 with a range from 1 to 7). These figures thus represent a typical number of ant species found on street trees in urbanized areas in Korea and Japan. However, the ant richness and composition were influenced by tree species and size.

The highest value of ant richness and number of nests were recorded from P. × yedoensis. Prunus × yedoensis has extra‐floral nectaries on the petiole near the base of the leaves and the trunks tend to decay around the junctions of branches after the latter fall off. Thus, this species provides both food and nest sites for ants. This could explain the frequent occurrence of ants on P. × yedoensis compared with that on other tree species (Harada 2011).

Out of the 17 species, three species (17.6%) nested in the trees but only two of those (11.8% of the total), Cr. matsumurai and Cr. vagula, are considered principally arboreal nesters (Harada 2011; Seifert 2008). However, these two species were not observed together on any single individual tree; this result is consistent with that of Harada (2011). Seven species nested on the ground surface or in the soil of the root zone. Some of these species, including L. japonicus, N. flavipes, T. tsushimae, and B. chinensis are particularly common in urban green spaces in East Asia (Park et al. 2014; Park & Moon 2005). For the remaining eight species, although nests were not located on trees, ants foraged on or near the trees.

In conclusion, the structure of ant assemblages on street trees planted in urban areas is influenced by the species of tree. In addition, the ant species that coexist on a single tree vary. The potential value of street trees for urban biodiversity must be recognized.
